e bug is not in the LLM or GitHub API, but in the automation's orchestration logic.","test_description":"Arrange: Use a real LLM (or deterministic mock if consistent output is acceptable) to generate 3-5 findings for a sample PR. Act: Run the full automation: (1) generate findings, (2) post each as an inline comment, (3) generate the summary. Capture the findings list and summary text. Assert: For each finding in the findings list, verify that a corresponding inline comment was posted (check the comment collection or API call log). For each comment posted, verify that it appears in the summary. Assert that no findings appear in the summary without a matching comment, and no posted comments are missing from the summary. Test both the happy path (all findings → all comments → all in summary) and edge cases (0 findings, 1 finding, duplicate findings).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration level is appropriate: multiple modules wired together (findings generation, comment posting, summary generation), no real external API calls needed (can use mocks for GitHub if necessary), but requires realistic data flow to catch orchestration bugs. A unit test of each component in isolation would miss the integration failure.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary comment — completes correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is a full agent pipeline with multiple real dependencies: (1) read a real PR diff (system boundary, real GitHub API), (2) LLM identifies findings (agentic boundary, non-deterministic), (3) post inline comments (system boundary, real GitHub API), (4) post summary (system boundary, real GitHub API). MOCK-MISS: Mocking any of these layers could hide failures. For example, mocking the LLM could pass 